    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That is the million-dollar question, and it's the one that kept the greatest physicists awake at night, often with a cup of tea and a very serious look on their face. They called it \"hidden variables\"—the idea that the particles were just secretly carrying little tags inside them, like a secret note passed between the twins, telling them what to do.\n\nBut in 1964, a brilliant man named John Bell figured out a way to test this. He created a mathematical test, now known as **Bell's Theorem**, which basically says: if the particles were just following a pre-written script (hidden variables), the results of their measurements would have to follow a certain pattern. But if they are truly entangled and \"spooky,\" they will break that pattern.\n\nPhysicists took real particles, separated them by miles (or even kilometers), and measured them in different ways. Every single time, the results violated Bell's inequality. It's like rolling two dice that are perfectly synchronized, but in a way that is mathematically impossible for any pre-determined pair of dice. The universe itself is refusing to let us have our \"hidden notes\" cake and eat it too.\n\nSo, we know it",
